PAIGNS, MUSIC VIDEOS, PRESS COVERAGE|last=Bridges|first=Angelica|date= |website=Vimeo|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>). That is until a store clerk<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=August 27, 1998|title=And the Winner Is ...|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1998-aug-27-fi-16964-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> ([[Brian Klugman]]) yanks the [[Virtual reality|virtual reality]] [[Virtual reality headset|device]] that produced her. The clerk tells the man that he put himself above his [[Visa Inc.|Visa]] [[Credit limit|credit card limit]]. Unlike Visa, [[American Express]] has no pre-set limits. A [[Tug of war|tug-of-war]] quickly ensues between the man and the clerk, which ultimately results in the [[Police|police]] being called.\n\n==Reception==\nThe commercial was [[50th Primetime Emmy Awards|nominated]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/tv/features/emmynomlist98.htm|title=1998 Emmy Nominations|last= |first= |date=July 23, 1998|website=Washington Post|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Elliott|first=Stuart|date=July 28, 1998|title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS: ADVERTISING -- ADDENDA; TV Ads Nominated For Emmy Awards|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/28/business/the-media-business-advertising-addenda-tv-ads-nominated-for-emmy-awards.html|work=The New York Times|location= |access-date= }}</ref> for an [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Commercial|Emmy for Outstanding Commercial]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/american-express-virtual-reality|title=American Express - Virtual Reality |last= |first= |date= |website=Television Academy|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1998-jul-24-fi-6630-story.html|title=L.A. Basks in Glow of Ads Up for Emmy|last=Gellene|first=Denise|date=July 24, 1998|website=Los Angeles Times|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>, ultimately losing out to [[Apple, Inc.|Apple Computer]]'s \"[[Think different|Think Different]]\" advertisement.\n\nAngelica Bridges, who portrayed to the red-headed beauty was compared to a modern day [[Ginger Rogers]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/0KGAB8zNCb/|title=American Express Commercial \ud83d\udc83 #ballroomdancing #virtualreality#Tbt #emmynominated #fredastaire #gingerrodgers #screenshots #superbowlad|last=Bridges|first=Angelica|date=March 12, 2015|website=Instagram|publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>. Meanwhile, according to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', this particular ad helped\n[[Raymond O'Connor]], the hapless Visa user, land a role in the film ''[[My Giant]]''.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Virtual reality in fiction]]\n*[[Dance_in_film#Ballroom]]\n*[[American_Express#Advertising_campaigns]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=11703472|title=American Express - Virtual Reality}}\n\n{{American Express}}\n{{Mixed reality}}\n\n[[Category:American Express|Virtual Reality]]\n[[Category:American television commercials]]\n[[Category:1998 works]]\n[[Category:1998 in American television]]\n[[Category:Virtual reality in fiction]]\n[[Category:Works about ballroom dance]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addedorphantag,typo(s) fixed: modern day \u2192 modern-day", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Express_-_Virtual_Reality_(advertisement)"}
{"title_page": "Waldeisenbahn Muskau", "text_new": "{{short description|German narrow-gauge railway in Saxony}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Waldeisenbahn Muskau<br />''Muskau forest railway''\n|image       = File:Bad Muskauer Bahn BR 99 3315-1..004.jpg\n|image_width = \n|caption     = Steam locomotive-hauled train in April 2017\n|type        = [[Industrial railway]] (until 1978)<br />[[Heritage railway]]\n|routenumber = \n|linenumber  = \n|linelength  = {{convert|20|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n|gauge       = {{Track gauge|600mm|lk=on}}\n|tracks      = \n|stations    = 12 stations<br />3 stops\n|ridership2  = 53.000 (2017)<ref name=\"lr23012019\">{{cite web |last=Wei\u00df |first=Regina |url=https://www.lr-online.de/lausitz/weisswasser/besuchermagnet-von-bad-muskau-die-waldeisenbahn-steuert-ein-grosses-jubilaeum-an-38160606.html |title=Die Waldeisenbahn steuert ein gro\u00dfes Jubil\u00e4um an |trans-title=The Waldeisenbahn is heading for a big anniversary |language=German |date=January 23, 2019 |work=Lausitzer Rundschau |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/k2cid |archivedate=April 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><br />47.000 (2018)<ref name=\"lr23012019\"/>\n|website     = {{URL|waldeisenbahn.de}}\n|map         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Waldeisenbahn Muskau''' is a {{Track gauge|600mm|lk=on}} narrow gauge railway connecting [[Kromlau]], [[Wei\u00dfwasser]] and [[Bad Muskau]] in [[Saxony]], Germany. It is the longest 600&nbsp;mm gauge [[heritage railway]] in Germany, with a track length of {{convert|20|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"swr14032014\">{{Cite episode |series=Eisenbahn-Romantik |title=Oberlausitzer Impressionen \u2013 Die Waldeisenbahn von Bad Muskau |trans-title=Upper Lusatian impressions \u2013 The forest railway of Bad Muskau |url=https://www.swrfernsehen.de/eisenbahn-romantik/folgen/broadcastcontrib-swr-36816.html |access-date=April 4, 2020 |series-link=Eisenbahn-Romantik |first=Susanne |last=Mayer-Hagmann |network=ARD |station=[[SWR Fernsehen]] |date=March 14, 2014 |number=812 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Wei\u00dfwasser - Tagebau Nochten - Turm am Schweren Berg 01 ies.jpg|thumb|Schwerer Berg observation tower, near the new terminus of the Tonbahn]]\nThe first tracks were laid in 1895. Operation began as a [[horse-drawn railway]], with the switch to [[steam locomotive]]s beginning in 1896.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/>\n\nTracks and rolling stock were damaged in the [[Second World War]], after which [[World War II reparations|reparations]] further restricted the operation of the Waldeisenbahn Muskau.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/>\n\nIn 1951 the Waldeisenbahn was incorporated into the [[Deutsche Reichsbahn (East Germany)|Reichsbahn]].<ref name=\"bb29042016\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bautzenerbote.de/eisbahnromantik-in-muskau-erleben/ |title=Eisenbahnromantik erleben |trans-title=Experience railway romance |language=German |date=April 29, 2016 |work=Bautzener Bote |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/CEI9t |archivedate=April 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On March 21, 1978 the Minister of Transport ordered the closure of the Waldeisenbahn Muskau, which was followed by an order on March 29 to cease operation by the Cottbus railway directorate ({{lang-de|Reichsbahndirektion Cottbus}}).<ref name=\"lr27032018\">{{cite web |last=Nitsche |first=Gabi |url=https://www.lr-online.de/lausitz/weisswasser/in-manchem-abschied-steckt-ein-neubeginn_aid-8153755 |title=In manchem Abschied steckt ein Neubeginn |trans-title=There is a new beginning in some goodbyes |language=German |date=March 27, 2018 |work=Lausitzer Rundschau |access-date=April 3, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/4jRW7 |archivedate=October 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter 1978 only {{convert|10|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} of track remained in use between Wei\u00dfwasser and a [[brickyard]], with occasional special services run by [[rail enthusiast]]s.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/> First efforts to preserve the Waldeisenbahn Muskau were made by rail enthusiasts beginning in the 1980s.<ref name=\"lr03102018\">{{cite web |last=Richter-Zippack |first=Torsten |url=https://www.lr-online.de/lausitz/weisswasser/erfolgsgeschichte-waldeisenbahn-bad-muskau_aid-33459321 |title=Erfolgsgeschichte Waldeisenbahn |trans-title=Success story Waldeisenbahn |language=German |date=October 3, 2018 |work=Lausitzer Rundschau |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/d0x7I |archivedate=October 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> A construction staff<!--Aufbaustab--> was established by the [[Districts of Germany|district]] of Wei\u00dfwasser in 1991.<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/> The line between Wei\u00dfwasser and Kromlau reopened in 1992, with tourist services beginning the same year.<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/> The line to Bad Muskau was reopened in 1995. In the 1990s many people, as many as 100 simultaneously, were involved in the Waldeisenbahn as part of {{lang|de|Arbeitsbeschaffungsma\u00dfnahmen|italic=yes}} (job creation programs).<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/>\n\nThe Waldeisenbahn Muskau took over the {{lang|de|Tonbahn|italic=yes}} (clay railway) between Wei\u00dfwasser and the M\u00fchlrose [[clay pit]] in 2010.<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/> Operations on the {{lang|de|Tonbahn|italic=yes}} ceased in 2014 due to the expansion of the {{ill|Tagebau Nochten|de}} [[open pit mine]].<ref name=\"mdr25122019\">{{Cite episode |series=Auf schmaler Spur |title=Z\u00fcgig durch die Lausitz |trans-title=Briskly through Lusatia |url=https://www.mdr.de/tv/programm/video-368146_zc-12fce4ab_zs-6102e94c.html |access-date=April 4, 2020 |first= |last= |network=ARD |station=[[Mitteldeutscher Rundfunk]] |date=December 25, 2019 |number= |language=German}}</ref> A new {{convert|3.5|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} alignment of the ''Tonbahn'' was inaugurated in April 2017,<ref name=\"radiolausitz\">{{cite AV media |last1=Kunoth |first1=Knut-Michael |last2=Lichnok |first2=Heiko |title=Freie Fahrt zum Schweren Berg in Wei\u00dfwasser |trans-title=The line is clear to the Schwerer Berg in Wei\u00dfwasser |date=April 13, 2017 |medium=Radio broadcast |language=German |url=https://www.radiolausitz.de/beitrag/freie-fahrt-zum-schweren-berg-in-weisswasser-444609/ |access-date=April 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/fWImt |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live |publisher=Radio Lausitz}}</ref> with the former alignment being dismantled to make way for the open pit mine. The new terminus is located near the Schwerer Berg [[observation tower]].<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/>\n\nA new maintenance [[Railway workshop|workshop]] was inaugurated in 2019,<ref name=\"lr15082019\">{{cite web |last=K\u00f6hler |first=Wolfgang |url=https://www.lr-online.de/lausitz/weisswasser/waldeisenbahn-muskau-der-winterbetrieb-kann-nun-kommen-38333226.html |title=Der Winterbetrieb kann nun kommen |trans-title=Winter operation can come now |language=German |date=August 15, 2019 |work=Lausitzer Rundschau |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/kybjz |archivedate=April 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> eliminating the need to transport the locomotives to maintenance companies with [[Lowboy (trailer)|lowboy trailers]].<ref name=\"mdr25122019\"/>\n\n==Network==\nAt its peak the network had a length of over {{convert|80|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/> Most of the tracks were removed following the closure of the network in 1978.<ref name=\"mdr25122019\"/> The rebuilt network between Kromlau, Wei\u00dfwasser and Bad Muskau has a length of {{convert|20|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/> {{As of|2018|10}}, it has 12 stations<!--({{lang-de|Bahnh\u00f6fe}})--> and three stops<!--({{lang-de|Haltepunkte}})-->.<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/>\n\n==Rolling stock==\nUntil its closure in 1978 the Waldeisenbahn was only operated as an [[industrial railway]], with the fleet consisting of multiple steam locomotives, diesel locomotives for shunting, and over 550 [[railway car]]s in total.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/> Some of the original rolling stock is still used for heritage operation. Other rolling stock has been acquired from [[pit railway]]s and {{lang|de|[[Feldbahn]]|italic=yes}} systems. The current fleet consists of steam locomotives, 31 [[diesel locomotive]]s, passenger cars and freight cars.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/>\n\n[[Heeresfeldbahnlokomotive]] HF 2257 from the {{ill|Cottbuser Parkeisenbahn|de}} was used on a special event for [[railfan]]s on October 12 and 13, 2019.<ref name=\"lok12112019\">{{cite web |last=van Sten |first=Ad |url=https://www.lok-report.de/news/deutschland/museum/item/14418-ein-gast-auf-der-waldeisenbahn-muskau.html |title=Ein Gast auf der Waldeisenbahn Muskau |trans-title=A guest at the Waldeisenbahn Muskau |language=German |date=November 12, 2019 |website=lok-report.de |publisher=Lokomotive Fachbuchhandlung |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/remHW |archivedate=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:99 3317 Borsig 10306-18 - Flickr - kevinprince3.jpg|99 3317\nFile:Bad Muskauer Bahn BR 99 3462..008.jpg|99 3462\nFile:Diesellok Waldeisenbahn Muskau (5681043146).jpg|K\u00f6 0451\nFile:Bad Muskauer Bahn K\u00f6 0472..011.jpg|K\u00f6 0472\nFile:Ziegelwagen Reihe 05.JPG|Type 05 freight car for brick transport\nFile:Bad Muskauer Bahn BR 99 3315-1..031.jpg|Passenger cars\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Tischer |first=Friedemann |title=Die Muskauer Waldeisenbahn |trans-title=The Muskau forest railway |language=German |date=2003 |publisher=Verlag Kenning |isbn=3-933613-63-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{officialwebsite|1=http://www.waldeisenbahn.de/}} {{in lang|de}}\n\n[[Category:Transport in Saxony]]\n[[Category:600 mm gauge railways in Germany]]\n[[Category:Heritage railways in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German narrow-gauge railway in Saxony}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n|name        = Waldeisenbahn Muskau<br />''Muskau forest railway''\n|image       = File:Bad Muskauer Bahn BR 99 3315-1..004.jpg\n|image_width = \n|caption     = Steam locomotive-hauled train in April 2017\n|type        = [[Industrial railway]] (until 1978)<br />[[Heritage railway]]\n|routenumber = \n|linenumber  = \n|linelength  = {{convert|20|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n|gauge       = {{Track gauge|600mm|lk=on}}\n|tracks      = \n|stations    = 12 stations<br />3 stops\n|ridership2  = 53.000 (2017)<ref name=\"lr23012019\">{{cite web |last=Wei\u00df |first=Regina |url=https://www.lr-online.de/lausitz/weisswasser/besuchermagnet-von-bad-muskau-die-waldeisenbahn-steuert-ein-grosses-jubilaeum-an-38160606.html |title=Die Waldeisenbahn steuert ein gro\u00dfes Jubil\u00e4um an |trans-title=The Waldeisenbahn is heading for a big anniversary |language=German |date=January 23, 2019 |work=Lausitzer Rundschau |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/k2cid |archivedate=April 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><br />47.000 (2018)<ref name=\"lr23012019\"/>\n|website     = {{URL|waldeisenbahn.de}}\n|map         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Waldeisenbahn Muskau''' is a {{Track gauge|600mm|lk=on}} narrow gauge railway connecting [[Kromlau]], [[Wei\u00dfwasser]] and [[Bad Muskau]] in [[Saxony]], Germany. It is the longest 600 mm gauge [[heritage railway]] in Germany, with a track length of {{convert|20|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"swr14032014\">{{Cite episode |series=Eisenbahn-Romantik |title=Oberlausitzer Impressionen \u2013 Die Waldeisenbahn von Bad Muskau |trans-title=Upper Lusatian impressions \u2013 The forest railway of Bad Muskau |url=https://www.swrfernsehen.de/eisenbahn-romantik/folgen/broadcastcontrib-swr-36816.html |access-date=April 4, 2020 |series-link=Eisenbahn-Romantik |first=Susanne |last=Mayer-Hagmann |network=ARD |station=[[SWR Fernsehen]] |date=March 14, 2014 |number=812 |language=German}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Wei\u00dfwasser - Tagebau Nochten - Turm am Schweren Berg 01 ies.jpg|thumb|Schwerer Berg observation tower, near the new terminus of the Tonbahn]]\nThe first tracks were laid in 1895. Operation began as a [[horse-drawn railway]], with the switch to [[steam locomotive]]s beginning in 1896.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/>\n\nTracks and rolling stock were damaged in the [[Second World War]], after which [[World War II reparations|reparations]] further restricted the operation of the Waldeisenbahn Muskau.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/>\n\nIn 1951 the Waldeisenbahn was incorporated into the [[Deutsche Reichsbahn (East Germany)|Reichsbahn]].<ref name=\"bb29042016\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bautzenerbote.de/eisbahnromantik-in-muskau-erleben/ |title=Eisenbahnromantik erleben |trans-title=Experience railway romance |language=German |date=April 29, 2016 |work=Bautzener Bote |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/CEI9t |archivedate=April 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On March 21, 1978 the Minister of Transport ordered the closure of the Waldeisenbahn Muskau, which was followed by an order on March 29 to cease operation by the Cottbus railway directorate ({{lang-de|Reichsbahndirektion Cottbus}}).<ref name=\"lr27032018\">{{cite web |last=Nitsche |first=Gabi |url=https://www.lr-online.de/lausitz/weisswasser/in-manchem-abschied-steckt-ein-neubeginn_aid-8153755 |title=In manchem Abschied steckt ein Neubeginn |trans-title=There is a new beginning in some goodbyes |language=German |date=March 27, 2018 |work=Lausitzer Rundschau |access-date=April 3, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/4jRW7 |archivedate=October 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter 1978 only {{convert|10|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} of track remained in use between Wei\u00dfwasser and a [[brickyard]], with occasional special services run by [[rail enthusiast]]s.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/> First efforts to preserve the Waldeisenbahn Muskau were made by rail enthusiasts beginning in the 1980s.<ref name=\"lr03102018\">{{cite web |last=Richter-Zippack |first=Torsten |url=https://www.lr-online.de/lausitz/weisswasser/erfolgsgeschichte-waldeisenbahn-bad-muskau_aid-33459321 |title=Erfolgsgeschichte Waldeisenbahn |trans-title=Success story Waldeisenbahn |language=German |date=October 3, 2018 |work=Lausitzer Rundschau |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/d0x7I |archivedate=October 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> A construction staff<!--Aufbaustab--> was established by the [[Districts of Germany|district]] of Wei\u00dfwasser in 1991.<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/> The line between Wei\u00dfwasser and Kromlau reopened in 1992, with tourist services beginning the same year.<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/> The line to Bad Muskau was reopened in 1995. In the 1990s many people, as many as 100 simultaneously, were involved in the Waldeisenbahn as part of {{lang|de|Arbeitsbeschaffungsma\u00dfnahmen|italic=yes}} (job creation programs).<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/>\n\nThe Waldeisenbahn Muskau took over the {{lang|de|Tonbahn|italic=yes}} (clay railway) between Wei\u00dfwasser and the M\u00fchlrose [[clay pit]] in 2010.<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/> Operations on the {{lang|de|Tonbahn|italic=yes}} ceased in 2014 due to the expansion of the {{ill|Tagebau Nochten|de}} [[open pit mine]].<ref name=\"mdr25122019\">{{Cite episode |series=Auf schmaler Spur |title=Z\u00fcgig durch die Lausitz |trans-title=Briskly through Lusatia |url=https://www.mdr.de/tv/programm/video-368146_zc-12fce4ab_zs-6102e94c.html |access-date=April 4, 2020 |first= |last= |network=ARD |station=[[Mitteldeutscher Rundfunk]] |date=December 25, 2019 |number= |language=German}}</ref> A new {{convert|3.5|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} alignment of the ''Tonbahn'' was inaugurated in April 2017,<ref name=\"radiolausitz\">{{cite AV media |last1=Kunoth |first1=Knut-Michael |last2=Lichnok |first2=Heiko |title=Freie Fahrt zum Schweren Berg in Wei\u00dfwasser |trans-title=The line is clear to the Schwerer Berg in Wei\u00dfwasser |date=April 13, 2017 |medium=Radio broadcast |language=German |url=https://www.radiolausitz.de/beitrag/freie-fahrt-zum-schweren-berg-in-weisswasser-444609/ |access-date=April 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/fWImt |archive-date=April 2, 2020 |url-status=live |publisher=Radio Lausitz}}</ref> with the former alignment being dismantled to make way for the open pit mine. The new terminus is located near the Schwerer Berg [[observation tower]].<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/>\n\nA new maintenance [[Railway workshop|workshop]] was inaugurated in 2019,<ref name=\"lr15082019\">{{cite web |last=K\u00f6hler |first=Wolfgang |url=https://www.lr-online.de/lausitz/weisswasser/waldeisenbahn-muskau-der-winterbetrieb-kann-nun-kommen-38333226.html |title=Der Winterbetrieb kann nun kommen |trans-title=Winter operation can come now |language=German |date=August 15, 2019 |work=Lausitzer Rundschau |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/kybjz |archivedate=April 4, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> eliminating the need to transport the locomotives to maintenance companies with [[Lowboy (trailer)|lowboy trailers]].<ref name=\"mdr25122019\"/>\n\n==Network==\nAt its peak the network had a length of over {{convert|80|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/> Most of the tracks were removed following the closure of the network in 1978.<ref name=\"mdr25122019\"/> The rebuilt network between Kromlau, Wei\u00dfwasser and Bad Muskau has a length of {{convert|20|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/> {{As of|2018|10}}, it has 12 stations<!--({{lang-de|Bahnh\u00f6fe}})--> and three stops<!--({{lang-de|Haltepunkte}})-->.<ref name=\"lr03102018\"/>\n\n==Rolling stock==\nUntil its closure in 1978 the Waldeisenbahn was only operated as an [[industrial railway]], with the fleet consisting of multiple steam locomotives, diesel locomotives for shunting, and over 550 [[railway car]]s in total.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/> Some of the original rolling stock is still used for heritage operation. Other rolling stock has been aquired from [[pit railway]]s and {{lang|de|[[Feldbahn]]|italic=yes}} systems. The current fleet consists of steam locomotives, 31 [[diesel locomotive]]s, passenger cars and freight cars.<ref name=\"swr14032014\"/>\n\n[[Heeresfeldbahnlokomotive]] HF 2257 from the {{ill|Cottbuser Parkeisenbahn|de}} was used on a special event for [[railfan]]s on October 12 and 13, 2019.<ref name=\"lok12112019\">{{cite web |last=van Sten |first=Ad |url=https://www.lok-report.de/news/deutschland/museum/item/14418-ein-gast-auf-der-waldeisenbahn-muskau.html |title=Ein Gast auf der Waldeisenbahn Muskau |trans-title=A guest at the Waldeisenbahn Muskau |language=German |date=November 12, 2019 |website=lok-report.de |publisher=Lokomotive Fachbuchhandlung |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/remHW |archivedate=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:99 3317 Borsig 10306-18 - Flickr - kevinprince3.jpg|99 3317\nFile:Bad Muskauer Bahn BR 99 3462..008.jpg|99 3462\nFile:Diesellok Waldeisenbahn Muskau (5681043146).jpg|K\u00f6 0451\nFile:Bad Muskauer Bahn K\u00f6 0472..011.jpg|K\u00f6 0472\nFile:Ziegelwagen Reihe 05.JPG|Type 05 freight car for brick transport\nFile:Bad Muskauer Bahn BR 99 3315-1..031.jpg|Passenger cars\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last=Tischer |first=Friedemann |title=Die Muskauer Waldeisenbahn |trans-title=The Muskau forest railway |language=German |date=2003 |publisher=Verlag Kenning |isbn=3-933613-63-9}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n*{{officialwebsite|1=http://www.waldeisenbahn.de/}} {{in lang|de}}\n\n[[Category:Transport in Saxony]]\n[[Category:600 mm gauge railways in Germany]]\n[[Category:Heritage railways in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: aquired \u2192 acquired", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waldeisenbahn_Muskau"}
{"title_page": "Jonna Curtis", "text_new": "{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1994|2|28|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Elk River]], [[Minnesota]], [[United States of America]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_cm = 163\n| weight_lb = \n| position = [[Forward (ice hockey)]]\n| shoots = Right\n| team = [[Minnesota Whitecaps]]\n| league = [[NWHL]]\n| played_for = [[University of New Hampshire]]\n| ntl_team = \n| draft = \n| draft_year = \n| draft_team = \n| career_start = 2018\n| career_end = \n}}\n\n'''Jonna Curtis''' is an American [[ice hockey]] forward currently playing for the [[Minnesota Whitecaps]] of the [[NWHL]], who she joined for their inaugural NWHL season in 2018\u201319. Prior to that, she captained the University of New Hampshire putting up 106 points in 161 games and twice earning a Hockey East All-Star Honorable Mention.<ref>https://whitecaps.nwhl.zone/stats#/player/431666/bio</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAs a youth player, Curtis was a finalist for the Minnesota Ms. Hockey award in 2012, and set the Elk River High School scoring records of points and assists.<ref>https://www.elkriverhockey.org/walloffame</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/08/sports/hockey/minnesota-whitecaps-nwhl.html</ref><ref>https://www.hometownsource.com/elk_river_star_news/sports/elks-jonna-curtis-named-to-ms-hockey-final-five/article_9cd03098-2aa6-5eab-ae24-cb35e62d454f.html</ref>\n\nAfter the 2018\u201319 season, she was named NWHL Newcomer of the Year, and was named to both the 2019 and 2020 NWHL all-star teams,<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2020/2/7/21123065/how-to-watch-2020-nwhl-all-star-game-weekend-preview-twitch-womens-hockey-boston</ref> playing as one of the top scorers for the Whitecaps.<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/12/30/21034550/minnesota-whitecaps-mid-season-report-card-nwhl-womens-hockey</ref><ref>https://victorypress.org/2020/03/10/nwhl-isobel-cup-final-2020-preview/</ref> In 2019, the Whitecaps won the [[Isobel Cup]], and made it to the finals in 2020, before the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] indefinitely postponed the game.<ref>https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-whitecaps-play-for-second-straight-trip-to-nwhl-championship-game/568597362/</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nCurtis was originally planning on retiring from hockey after her university career, until the NWHL expansion to Minnestoa was announced.<ref>https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/why-the-nwhls-leading-scorer-is-among-the-biggest-surprises-of-the-season</ref> Outside of hockey, Curtis works as an engineer.<ref>https://thehockeywriters.com/minnesota-whitecaps-jonna-curtis-interview/</ref><ref>https://grandstandcentral.com/2019/sections/gender/when-professional-hockey-is-your-side-hustle/</ref>\n\n== Stats ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"50%\"\n|- align=\"center\" style=\" background:blue; color:#FFFFFF;\"\n| '''Season''' || '''Team''' || '''Games played''' || '''Goals''' || '''Assists'''|| '''Points'''|| '''PIM'''|| '''+/-'''|| '''S%'''|| '''Blocked Shots'''\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\" \"\n|2018-19 ||Minnesota Whitecaps || 16 || 8 || 11 || 19 || 12 || +10 || - || -\n|-\n|2019-20 ||Minnesota Whitecaps || 21 || 14 || 22 || 36 || 10 || +25 || 17,1 || 14\n|-\n|}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://whitecaps.nwhl.zone/stats#/player/431666/stats}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* Biographical information and career statistics from the Internet Hockey Database<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=217896 |website=Internet Hockey Databse}}</ref> and Elite Prospects<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/399305/jonna-curtis |website=Elite Propsects}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Minnesota Whitecaps players]]\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-icehockey-player-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1994|2|28|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Elk River]], [[Minnesota]], [[United States of America]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_cm = 163\n| weight_lb = \n| position = [[Forward (ice hockey)]]\n| shoots = Right\n| team = [[Minnesota Whitecaps]]\n| league = [[NWHL]]\n| played_for = [[University of New Hampshire]]\n| ntl_team = \n| draft = \n| draft_year =  \n| draft_team =  \n| career_start = 2018\n| career_end =  \n}}\n\n'''Jonna Curtis''' is an American [[ice hockey]] forward currently playing for the [[Minnesota Whitecaps]] of the [[NWHL]], who she joined for their inaugural NWHL season in 2018-19. Prior to that, she captained the University of New Hampshire putting up 106 points in 161 games and twice earning a Hockey East All-Star Honorable Mention.<ref>https://whitecaps.nwhl.zone/stats#/player/431666/bio</ref> \n\n== Career ==\n\nAs a youth player, Curtis was a finalist for the Minnesota Ms. Hockey award in 2012, and set the Elk River High School scoring records of points and assists.<ref>https://www.elkriverhockey.org/walloffame</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/08/sports/hockey/minnesota-whitecaps-nwhl.html</ref><ref>https://www.hometownsource.com/elk_river_star_news/sports/elks-jonna-curtis-named-to-ms-hockey-final-five/article_9cd03098-2aa6-5eab-ae24-cb35e62d454f.html</ref>\n\nAfter the 2018-19 season, she was named NWHL Newcomer of the Year, and was named to both the 2019 and 2020 NWHL all-star teams<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2020/2/7/21123065/how-to-watch-2020-nwhl-all-star-game-weekend-preview-twitch-womens-hockey-boston</ref>, playing as one of the top scorers for the Whitecaps.<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/12/30/21034550/minnesota-whitecaps-mid-season-report-card-nwhl-womens-hockey</ref><ref>https://victorypress.org/2020/03/10/nwhl-isobel-cup-final-2020-preview/</ref> In 2019, the Whitecaps won the [[Isobel Cup]], and made it to the finals in 2020, before the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] indefinitely postponed the game.<ref>https://www.startribune.com/minnesota-whitecaps-play-for-second-straight-trip-to-nwhl-championship-game/568597362/</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\n\nCurtis was originally planning on retiring from hockey after her university career, until the NWHL expansion to Minnestoa was announced.<ref>https://thehockeynews.com/news/article/why-the-nwhls-leading-scorer-is-among-the-biggest-surprises-of-the-season</ref> Outside of hockey, Curtis works as an engineer.<ref>https://thehockeywriters.com/minnesota-whitecaps-jonna-curtis-interview/</ref><ref>https://grandstandcentral.com/2019/sections/gender/when-professional-hockey-is-your-side-hustle/</ref>\n\n== Stats == \n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" width=\"50%\"\n|- align=\"center\"  style=\" background:blue; color:#FFFFFF;\"\n| '''Season''' || '''Team''' ||  '''Games played''' || '''Goals''' || '''Assists'''|| '''Points'''|| '''PIM'''|| '''+/-'''|| '''S%'''|| '''Blocked Shots'''\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\" \"\n|2018-19 ||Minnesota Whitecaps || 16 || 8 || 11 || 19 || 12 || +10  || - || -\n|-\n|2019-20 ||Minnesota Whitecaps || 21 || 14 || 22 || 36 || 10 || +25 || 17,1 || 14\n|-\n|}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://whitecaps.nwhl.zone/stats#/player/431666/stats}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* Biographical information and career statistics from the Internet Hockey Database<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/pdisplay.php?pid=217896 |website=Internet Hockey Databse}}</ref> and Elite Prospects<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/399305/jonna-curtis |website=Elite Propsects}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{US-icehockey-player-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Minnesota Whitecaps players]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesmcmahon0", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 2018-19 \u2192 2018\u201319, 2018-19 \u2192 2018\u201319", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonna_Curtis"}
